This will happen when the Fed raises interest rates.
An interest rate hike is coming, and the rise will fluctuate, yields on bonds will rise, and the economy will slide into recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long all this will take and how long it will last.
In particular, history offers little guidance for the economy on how to proceed.
A recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial investments react.
Therefore, representatives of the U.S. Central Bank have emphasized so strongly that investors should not focus on when they begin to raise interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants might find that the whole excitement about an interest rate hike may have been exaggerated.
“The Fed’s first increase since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of ‘cheap money’,” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement to clients.
In contrast, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to normal levels, but still at too low a level to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here’s a look at how some areas of the economy might react based on historical trends:
As the market has seen in the past month, anticipating interest rate hikes can make things volatile for a while.
As soon as the increase comes in, the impact is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency for asset returns to be strangled 12 to 24 months after the first raise, which may again reflect the delay in monetary policy,” Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of what happens after interest rate hikes by the Fed.
In fact, over the past 35 years, the market has been mostly on the upward trend - about 14 percent - on the way to interest rate increase, fairly flat at the 250 days after that (average gain of 2.6 percent), then back to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the past six cycles of 14 percent.
Deutsche Bank said that the impact on stocks tended to occur later in the rise cycle, and returns began to decline.
Recession is a fact of economic life, but interest rate hikes often encourage it.
In the current case, the Fed is faced with some conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
It is extremely remarkable here that the gross domestic product will be near its lowest point at an interest rate increase of the Fed.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 rate hikes since 1950 were only twice the nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Interest rate hikes under such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky and raise the question of “whether it’s different this time around,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have been gearing up for a Fed rate hike throughout the year, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading only gives a 25 percent chance.
“In our study, all of the increase cycles from 1950 to today took place in a super cycle with increasing momentum in GDP and put pre-recession highs in the shadows very quickly after the onset of recovery,” the report said.
In contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate increase, and the pattern is quite similar to that on the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic price.
In the case of bonds, the returns appear to change direction as soon as the first increase/decrease in the cycle takes place.
At the end of the raising cycle, bond yields fall immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
Charles Schwab’s strategists believe that the rise in interest rates will bring yields closer together between longer and shorter bonds and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-interest bonds often bring better returns in such a climate, though “we’re still cautious about expecting higher returns,” Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that the markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations.
“Besides the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of tightening monetary policy,” she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is flatter, credit spreads have widened, and volatility has risen — all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
On the whole, companies that do most of their business in the U.S. will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debt will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market and also financing their debt.
