At their most anticipated meeting of the year, Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27-foot Honduras mahogany table to decide if it’s time to raise interest rates for the first time in nearly a decade.
Threatening above them at one end of the ornate, two-story meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The card is a reminder that Fed Chair Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the nation’s economic interests ahead of everything else.
The central bank has a two-fold mandate from Congress to keep U.S. employment and prices stable here.
But since the Great Recession, the Fed leaders have recognized that there is an unwritten third mandate: financial stability.
And this third mandate could be the X factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict, and it will be announced on Thursday whether the U.S. economy is ready to be weaned off the unprecedented stimulus by the near-zero short-term interest rate since the end of 2008.
Although most economic data shows that it is growing solidly, the recent turbulence in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials into stepping up this volatility by raising interest rates on federal bonds — and even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labor market and inflation will be primarily the most important thing they observe," said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for a pretext not to raise the interest rate, the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to keep waiting,” she said.
There is no consensus on what the Fed will do, which in itself insures the financial market.
About half of economists polled by Bloomberg recently predicted an interest rate hike this week.
However, financial markets expect the Fed to wait, with a key indicator showing only a 30% chance of an increase.
This indicates a decline in the stock market if the Fed raises the rate, unless the strategists mitigate the blow by promising that a further increase is far away.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average jumped 228.89 points or 1.4% to 16,599.85.
The action was triggered by expectations that Fed policy will maintain the rate this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
It would be a surprise if the Fed lifted the rates at that point,” he said.
If she does, “she would have to go very far in her statement to calm the financial markets so they don’t panic.”
Other experts argued that an interest rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed well on its way to raising the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month, the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of the recovery in the US.
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that this year, despite complaints from Liberals that more economic progress would be needed, she expected an increase in the rate.
Although job creation slowed in August, the improvement in the labour market this year was solid.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed sees as full employment.
Wage increases have shown signs of recovery.
And although inflation was consistently below the central bank’s 2% annual target, the Fed’s representatives said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices.
The economy "can handle higher interest rates and needs them because of the tension in the labor market," said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But financial markets around the world were collapsing late last month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell more than 16% below its peak in May, as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would throttle global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, with the Dow now almost 10% below the high of May.
For the Fed, market turbulence influences the complex calculation of when to raise interest rates.
“If the events in the financial markets and the news about the weakness of the Chinese economy hadn’t occurred in the last few weeks, they would have taken the reins in this session,” said Stephen D. Oliner, senior research fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former U.S. Bank employee.
Now he predicts that she will wait at least a month to get a better grip on the effects.
“There’s a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and there’s almost no reliable data describing developments in China,” Oliner said.
The health of the world economy is not a major concern of the Fed, so it should not be technically involved in its decision-making.
But in the end, the Fed has become the monetary authority of the world.
The influence of the central bank has been enormous in recent years.
The mere suggestion by then-leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “tighten” its monetary expansion triggered confusion around the globe.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed representatives can be expected to not only monitor developments elsewhere, but also consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
Their decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global asset management strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, VA, noted this month that "the Fed has a history of overreactions to financial market movements that are apparently not associated with the economic fundamentals."
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee who advocates an interest rate hike, cited decisions in 1998/1999 as an example.
A financial crisis in Asia led the Fed to lower its key interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions "despite limited discernible effects on U.S. growth," Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed’s representatives reversed these cuts.
The Fed should put aspects of financial stability first only during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market crash, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate-fixing committee.
Recent turbulence does not come close to this level, he said.
“She certainly doesn’t want to get into the situation where she’s afraid of an interest rate hike because the markets are getting upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains the double mandate and doesn’t mention financial stability, and until that is changed, I don’t think it should go ahead of time.
