In the presence of city president Ignazio Marino, a previously unnamed square in the park on the Oppio hill was christened on Wednesday in the name of the German reformer.
At the "Piazza Martin Luther" he is now recognized as a "German theologian of the Reformation".
The park is located in the middle of ancient Rome right next to the Colosseum.
The denomination had been requested by the working community of the evangelical churches in Rome.
Jens-Martin Kruse, pastor of the Evangelical Lutheran Church in Rome, recalled on Wednesday that Protestants in the city of the popes could often only live their faith in the occult over centuries as a minority.
With the square, it becomes symbolically visible that their tradition of the Christian faith in Rome is welcome.
Martin Luther (1483-1546) spent several months in Rome as a young Augustinian monk at the turn of the year 1510/11.
He felt the city at that time as a lost sinner.
His negative impressions may have strengthened him, according to historians, in his later struggle against Rome.
Luther then initiated the division of the Western Church with his theses against the indulgence trade.
