Robotic cars: government wants pioneering role for Germany
According to the will of the Federal Government, Germany should be technological pioneers in the transformation of the car.
The Federal Cabinet on Wednesday adopted a strategy paper from the house of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which includes investments in the expansion of digital infrastructure.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the sidelines of the IAA about a "new mobility era".
Automated and networked driving will increase road safety and reduce congestion, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his colleagues from the G7 countries, who will also meet with industry representatives at the IAA.
The strategy paper of the Ministry of Transport emphasizes, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid transition to digital radio.
To test new technology, a test track is currently being developed on Highway 9 in Bavaria.
In order to ensure that the driver "does not face any additional liability risks", the German government wants to "check the legal framework and, where necessary, adapt to the new developments".
For example, Germany wants to work internationally to increase the maximum permissible speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometers per hour.
The German government also wants to push for an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
With automated driving, the car is increasingly taking the lead, the driver is becoming more and more a passenger.
The technology is mainly based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study presented by the Ministry of Economy, highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020.
Nevertheless, driverless vehicles on public roads are “to be expected far beyond 2020”.
The authors estimate that the value added in the area of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at the German location for 2025 will be around <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>8.4 billion.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," said SPD transport politician S<0xC3><0xB6>ren Bartol.
However, the issue of liability in the event of accidents and the safety of the driver’s personal data must be clearly clarified.
However, the Germans still see self-driving cars skeptically - much more than the French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute commissioned by the testing organization Dekra, which was presented at the AA on Wednesday, found that only eight percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will prevail in the next ten years, 32 percent expect it in 20 years, and 31 percent do not believe it at all.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, in the United States, 33 percent.
After all, motorists in Germany are not yet ready to rely completely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to hand over control on all roads throughout the ride.
On the motorway, at least 15 percent could imagine this in flowing traffic, in traffic jams 45 percent.
Almost one in four would not leave the car in control under any circumstances.
