Xi Urges to Open the Economy Wider to the World
The economy must open wider to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping said on Tuesday, to a group tasked with steering the reform.
“China should strive to attract foreign investment and know-how and improve business start-up strategies,” he said in a speech at the 16th meeting of the Central Leadership Group for Deepening Comprehensive Reform.
Fostering new start-ups and pushing reforms will bring new momentum and vitality and provide new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The management group has adopted a number of guidelines, including a negative list to regulate market access, relax border control policies, promote state-owned enterprises (SOE), raise private capital, and overhaul the resident reporting system.
According to the statement, a negative list is created that identifies sectors and companies that are not eligible for investment.
The system is gradually tested and improved by testing programs.
The initiative is important because it assigns a greater role to the market in allocating resources, ensuring a rule of law business environment, and making the market more open, the statement said.
The government will also loosen controls over the powers transferred to the companies and ensure that companies decide how they conduct their business.
The statement also said that China will allow border areas to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
As part of an offer to open state-controlled sectors, further areas will be opened for private investment.
“The government will not change its policy towards foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide better services for them,” the statement said.
In addition, it will make it easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or the "Green Card" by optimizing the requirements and facilitating the application process.
The right of lawyers to be guaranteed to perform their duties and to employ professional judges and public prosecutors was also discussed at a meeting.
Premier Li Keqiang and key leaders such as Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli also attended the meeting, as reported in a statement released after the meeting.
EU wants to double mercury limit in predatory fish
The European Commission wants to double the limit values for mercury in large predatory fish and thereby give consumers a significantly higher dose of the nerve agent.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which has a corresponding EU working paper, sharply criticized the plans: "Risks and side effects of failed industrial and environmental policies are being passed on to pregnant women and young children with full force," said Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limit values of nerve poison for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, should be raised from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic reasons".
However, large predatory fish are already so heavily loaded with mercury that based on the limits still in force, about 50 percent of the catches may not be sold.
After doubling the limit values, then only 14.5 percent would be unsaleable.
In return for this relaxation, according to Foodwatch, the EU wants to tighten the limits for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram.
However, Foodwatch called this a “trick” because smaller peace fish, such as carp, are usually so low-stressed that they already meet the planned highs today.
The decline in small fish is therefore "a perfidious diversionary maneuver that helps the economy alone," Wolfschmidt explained.
Mercury is a heavy metal that is highly toxic to humans and is highly enriched in predatory fish, especially in the food chain.
The Federal Government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause damage to the nervous system, especially in the case of unborn children".
However, the Federal Ministry of the Environment explains on its homepage with regard to the current maximum values that a "health risk to the general population" is not to be expected.
Mercury enters the environment primarily through the burning of coal.
The German coal-fired power plants emit more than six tons of mercury per year, two-thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany, according to a written report by the Federal Ministry of the Environment to the Greens-Bundestag MP Annalena Baerbock.
The concentration of mercury in fish, such as in the Elbe, Rhine and Danube, was "permanently and comprehensively exceeded", the "mirror" had quoted from the paper in March.
Last year, Europe-wide warnings of mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU’s RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls on consumers to protest EU plans at: www.quecksilber-aktion.foodwatch.de
